<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: SHEPPARD M-SERIES - STEERING GEAR DISASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>STEERING GEAR DISASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="28">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <para>The diagnosis and troubleshooting section of this manual has been prepared to help with proper
                diagnosis. Repair time and downtime as well as repair costs can be reduced if needless disassembly and
                replacement of steering gear parts are avoided. Before removing the steering gear from the chassis, you
                must be certain that the hydraulic supply system is operating properly and that all mechanical
                components are in good repair.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>The Sheppard integral power steering gear is a precision machined assembly and care must be
                        taken during repair to keep it free of dirt and foreign material. All internal parts must be
                        handled carefully to avoid damages to machined surfaces. Nicks or burrs can cause damage to
                        mating parts and must be removed with a fine hand stone before reassembly. Working on a soft
                        cardboard or plywood surfaced workbench is best. Follow disassembly procedures as required.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <para>Remove the tab lock retainer and pitman arm. Refer to the
                <hotlnk document="s05002y_HL0500212.xml" xrefid="hl0500212">PITMAN ARM, REMOVE</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the rubber sector shaft boot (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500246">Figure 46</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500246" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500246" filename="../figg05/g0500246.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 47. Remove Rubber Sector Shaft Boot</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the mounting bracket bolts and separate the mounting bracket from the steering
                    gear (if equipped) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500247">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500247" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500247" filename="../figg05/g0500247.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 48. Remove Mounting Bracket Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the dirt shield from the end of the sector shaft with an Allen wrench (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500248">Figure 48</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500248" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500248" filename="../figg05/g0500248.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 49. Remove Dirt Shield</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a center punch to make two reference marks on the bearing cap and corresponding
                    marks on the housing. A single reference mark should be made on the cylinder head and a
                    corresponding mark on the housing, so the gear can be reassembled in the same configuration (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500249">Figure 49</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500249" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500249" filename="../figg05/g0500249.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 50. Make Reference Marks</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>Wear safety glasses; sharp metal from the punch or housing can injure an eye.</para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the relief valve plungers from both ends of the gear. This will protect them from
                    damage during repair (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500250">Figure 50</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500250" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500250" filename="../figg05/g0500250.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 51. Remove Relief Valve Plungers</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the bolts attaching the sector shaft cover to the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500251">Figure 51</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500251" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500251" filename="../figg05/g0500251.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 52. Remove Sector Shaft Cover Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a soft hammer to tap on the end of the sector shaft to loosen the cover (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500252">Figure 52</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500252" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500252" filename="../figg05/g0500252.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 53. Loosen Cover</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Carefully slide the sector shaft and cover out of the housing. Slide the cover off the
                    sector shaft (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500253">Figure 53</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500253" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500253" filename="../figg05/g0500253.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 54. Slide Sector Shaft and Cover Out of Housing</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove and discard the cover O-ring and sector shaft seal (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500254">Figure 54</hotlnk>) or the 3-piece seal assembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500255">Figure 55</hotlnk>) (if equipped).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500254" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500254" filename="../figg05/g0500254.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 55. Remove Cover O-Ring and Sector Shaft Seal</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500255" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500255" filename="../figg05/g0500255.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 56. Remove 3-Piece Seal Assembly</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the cylinder head and discard both the seal ring and the tetra seal (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500256">Figure 56</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500257">Figure 57</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500256" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500256" filename="../figg05/g0500256.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 57. Remove Cylinder Head</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500257" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500257" filename="../figg05/g0500257.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 58. Discard Seal Ring and Tetra Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the face seal from the input shaft (if equipped) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500258">Figure 58</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500258" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500258" filename="../figg05/g0500258.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 59. Remove Face Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the attaching bolts from the bearing cap and turn the input shaft to free the
                    bearing cap assembly from the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500259">Figure 59</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500259" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500259" filename="../figg05/g0500259.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 60. Remove Bearing Cap Attaching Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>After the bearing cap assembly is free from the housing, keep the shaft stationary.
                            Binding of the shaft and shaft damage may occur if the shaft is removed at this time (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f0500259">Figure 59</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Carefully slide the piston and bearing cap assembly from the housing bore until the ball
                    guide retainer is located (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500260">Figure 60</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500260" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500260" filename="../figg05/g0500260.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 61. Slide Piston and Bearing Cap Assembly From Housing Bore</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>The ball guide retainer must be held in place. If not, the ball return guides and steel
                            balls will drop out of the assembly. Loss of the steel balls may occur (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f0500261">Figure 61</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f0500261" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500261" filename="../figg05/g0500261.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 62. Hold Ball Guide Retainer in Place</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Screw a small sheet metal screw into the ball guide retainer until 2 to 3 threads are
                    engaged. Use a pair of pliers to remove the ball guide retainer from the piston (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500262">Figure 62</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500263">Figure 63</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500262" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500262" filename="../figg05/g0500262.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 63. Remove Ball Guide Retainer</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500263" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500263" filename="../figg05/g0500263.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 64. Remove Ball Guide Retainer</caption>
                </figure>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">Piston Variation</emph>
                    - Some steering gears are equipped with a bolt on ball guide retainer. Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500264">Figure 64</hotlnk>,
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500265">Figure 65</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500266">Figure 66</hotlnk>
                    for disassembly.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500264" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500264" filename="../figg05/g0500264.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 65. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500265" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500265" filename="../figg05/g0500265.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="272px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 66. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500266" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500266" filename="../figg05/g0500266.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 67. Bolt On Ball Guide Retainer Disassembly</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>With bolt on retainers, remove the mounting bolts and ball guide retainer. Remove and
                            discard the seal ring from the retainer (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f0500265">Figure 65</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do not remove the piston at this time. Leave the piston in the housing with the ball
                    guide exposed (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500266">Figure 66</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the ball return guides. The steel balls are then free to roll out of the ball
                    cavity in the piston (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500267">Figure 67</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500268">Figure 68</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500267" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500267" filename="../figg05/g0500267.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 68. Remove Ball Return Guides</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500268" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500268" filename="../figg05/g0500268.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 69. Remove Steel Balls</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>It will be necessary to rotate the shaft in and out slightly to remove all the steel
                            balls. 24 steel balls are contained in the piston and must be removed before the input shaft
                            and bearing cap assembly removal can be completed.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After removal of the 24 balls, the input shaft and bearing cap assembly may be removed
                    from the piston. At this time the seal ring and tetra seal may be removed and discarded (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500269">Figure 69</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500270">Figure 70</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500269" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500269" filename="../figg05/g0500269.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 70. Remove Input Shaft and Bearing Cap Assembly</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0500270" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500270" filename="../figg05/g0500270.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 71. Remove Seal Ring and Tetra Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Carefully slide the piston from the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500271">Figure 71</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500271" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500271" filename="../figg05/g0500271.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 72. Slide Piston From Housing</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove and discard the sector shaft seal from the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500272">Figure 72</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500272" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500272" filename="../figg05/g0500272.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 73. Discard Sector Shaft Seal</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The steering gear is now disassembled. Necessary parts may be replaced as needed (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0500273">Figure 73</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0500273" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0500273" filename="../figg05/g0500273.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 74. Steering Gear Assembly</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
